Considerations for Short Codes in Service Cloud

When you use short codes, your business is required to follow carrier compliance requirements, industry standards, and applicable laws. Short codes are only supported in the US and Canada.

Standard SMS channels are scheduled for retirement, and we’re limiting the ability to create standard channels. To avoid service interruptions, upgrade your standard SMS channels to enhanced channels before February 14, 2026.

What are Short Codes?

Short codes are 5- or 6-digit phone numbers that have few limits on throughput, volume, or inbound-to-outbound ratios. They can be used for single-message and recurring-message programs. Your company's automated responses can be a maximum of 160 characters.

How are Short Code Messages Routed?

Short code channels use the same Omni-Channel routing as your other channels. Customers must opt in to receiving messages before your business can start sending them.

Opting in to Messages

Customers must enter their phone number in an online form, sign up at a point-of-sale location, or send a text to your short code number. This type of opt-in is called explicit opt-in. When a customer sends a text to your short code, we send them your opt-in prompt.

Opting Out of Messages

To stay compliant, you must allow Messaging users to opt-out of receiving text messages from your short code. Messaging users can opt out by texting the keywords STOP, STOPALL, CANCEL, END, QUIT, and UNSUBSCRIBE to your short code.

Requesting Help

You're required to send a compliant response when a Messaging user texts a help keyword to your short code. Your help response must contain certain details, including campaign name, description, help sources, disclaimer, and message frequency.

Using Custom Responses

Use custom keywords and responses to account for country-specific regulations or to share other information specific to your company.

Using Short Codes in Canada

Because Canada has two official languages—English and French—short code keywords and automated responses must account for both languages.
title: Considerations for Short Codes in Service Cloud
